Subsidence Insurance Public Law 98-473 authorized states and tribes with approved reclamation programs to use abandoned mine land funds to establish self-sustaining, individually administered programs to ensure private property against damage caused by land subsidence resulting from abandoned underground coal mines.
Implementing rules were promulgated in February 1986.
This mine opening, or entry portal, in Eastern Pennsylvania was abandoned in the early 1900's.
Today, a large quantity of acid mine drainage flows from the open portal polluting rivers many miles downstream.
Reclamation of this West Virginia abandoned mine site eliminated 6,000 linear feet of highwall and sealed four mine openings.
To prevent future damage, an under-drain was placed along the length of the highwall to collect drainage from auger holes.
Since no topsoil was available, the spoil was directseeded with a special seed mix.
Today this landscape bears little resemblance to its appearance before the abandoned highwalls and spoil were reclaimed.
